{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893026/1938022401/0082.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nMany Recipes Already Entered\nPost\u2019s Two Recipe Contests\nOthers Urged To Send Theirs\nIn At Once. Community\nRecipes Wanted.\nSince the announcement of the\ntwo \u201cAshe County Recipe Con\ntests\u201d, sponsored by The Post, la\ndies in various parts of the coun\nty have already submitted recipes\nfor the \u201cIndividual Homemakers\nContest\u201d, but as yet no \u201cCommuni\nty Recipes\u201d have been entered.\nAs pointed out in the rules, these\nare two separate contests and The\nPost is anxious for various organi\nzations, as well as the individual\nhousewives, to submit recipes rep\nresenting their communities. Some\nladies organization in the Helton\ncommunity, for example, should\nsend in one or more \u201cHELTON\nCOMMUNITY RECIPES\u201d. Os course\nwe would like for them to be more\nor less typical of the cooking in the\ncommunity, but that isn\u2019t absolute\nly essential.\nThe recipes do not have to be\noriginal\u2014just FAVORITES that\nyou have tried and found good.\nSend in yours at once.\nHere are a few recipes already\nentered:\nBUTTERSCOTCH PIE\n1 cup brown sugar\n3 tablespoons butter\n4 tablespooris cream\nCook this mixture until thick and\nbrown. The browner it is cooked,\nthe more butterscotch taste it has.\nTo this add: 1 cup milk, 6 level ta\nblespoons flour, 1 egg yolk.\nMix these ingredients together\nwell and stir into the first mixture,\nstirring constantly. Cook until\nthick and pour into baked pie crust.\nRuth Norris, Fleetwood, N. C.\nSMOTHERED CHICKEN\n(With Fried Dumplings)\nTake a chicken that has been cut\nup and salted over night. Roll each\npiece in flour and fry in butter or\nany shortening desired. When\nbrown on all sides, take out and\nput in steamer or any pan that has\na fitted lid. Season to taste with\nsalt and pepper, and pour about a,\npint of hot water over it Cover\nand simmer slowly\u2014either in oven\nor on top of stove\u2014for one or two\nhours.\nSet aside the pan the chicken was\nfried in until ready to fry the j\ndumplings. About thirty minutes\nbefore time to serve make a bis\ncuit dough, roll out very thin, cut\nin pieces two or three inches square,\nprick with fork and fry in hot\ngrease, or butter, in the .pan the\nchicken has been fried in.\nAround the edge of a rather deep\nplatter lap the fried squares one\nover the other, pile chicken in cen\nter and cover with a gravy made of j\nmilk, flour and all chicken scraps\nfrom pans used in cooking. Mrs.\nBlanch Robinson, Route 1, Box 73,\nWest Jefferson, N. Carolina.\nSPECIAL CHOCOLATE CAKE\nTake the beaten yolks of two\neggs, one-fourth cake of chocolate\ngrated, and one-half cup of milk.\nCook until it thickens, then set* to\ncool a little, while you cream one\nand one-half cupfuls of sugar, and\nThe New 1938\nEASY\n/Fl Jff the big capacity, compact and sturdy\nI I \u00ae*djpl Model ISB for 1938. But good looks isn't\nI I xu fl all\u2014 see l\u00b0 r yourself the\n11 s69q~ 1\n.11 \u201cI ~J SUPER-SAVINGS of the new SPIRALATOR\nup ffl washing action that saves clothes wear,\nBl .-n\u2014 ..J saves washing time, saves soap and hot\nI I&sJS water.\nJ SUPER-SAFETY of the new ARISTOCRAT\nI JBBHI Bl Wringer that insures complete protection\nI with its Guardian Bar Release, its Safety\n.?i BS|/\u00a73EIISI Zone Construction, its Automatic Roll Stop.\nI SUPER-SERVJCE of the new Bonderite Rust-\nw Proof treatment of sheet metal parts\u2014new\n'fv Baked Enamel finish that's chip-pjoof and\ncolor-fast.\nEasy Terms-Buy Now\nCENTRAL RADIO COMPANY\nWEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\none-fourth cup of butter. Pour one-\nof sweet milk into choco\nlate mixture, which will cool it\nenough, to add the butter and sugar.\nAdd 2 cupfuls of flour, and one tea\nspoon of soda in hot water. Flavor\nand bake in layers, using whites of\neggs for frosting. Mrs. Thomas\nPowers, Lansing, N. C.\nDRIED APPLE DUMPLINGS\n2 cups flour\n1-3 teaspoon salt\n1 teaspoon baking powder\nj 1 teaspoon soda\n1 tabjespoon (heaping) full lard\n2-3 cup sour milk\n2 cups dried tart apples cut very\nfine\nt Sift flour, salt, soda and baking\npowder; add lard, apples and milk,\nand mix to a firm dough. Roll on\nboard till half inch thick, cut out\nj j with biscuit cutter. Have kettle of\nboiling water. Drop biscuits into\nit, cover and let boil twenty min\nutes. Serve at once with cream and\nI sugar. Individual, Tested and True\nRecipe. Mrs. L. C. Tomlinson, West\nJefferson, N. C.\nSWEET POTATOES\nPare and cut in round slices, eight\nor ten medium sized sweet potatoes.\nPut in a baking dish or sauce pan,\nand add one cup of water, one' cup\nof sugar, brown or white, whichever\npreferred, and butter about the size\nof an egg. Let cook until tender,\nthen put in the oven and bake un\ntil light brown on top. Marshmal\nlows may be used if so desired. Rose\nB. Tyne, Lansing, N. C.\nObids News\nMrs. Clint Dillard was taken to\nthe Wilkes hospital for treatment\nlast week.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Colvard, of\nNorth Wilkesboro, spent the week\nend with Mrs. Colvard\u2019s parents,\nMr. and Mrs. R. S. McNeill.\nMr. and Mrs. John Crawford, of\nNorth Wilkesboro, spent last week\nend with Mr. Crawford\u2019s parents,\nMr. and Mrs. J. C. Crawford.\nj Mr. and Mrs. J. H. Colvard and\nMrs. Johnsie Colvard and Miss Flor\nende lAshlqy ispqht Sunday after\nnoon with Mr. and Mrs. Charles\nCalloway of West Jefferson.\nI Mr. Rom Phillips and family vis\nited Mr. and Mrs. John Phillips\nI Sunday.\nCORA DeBOREi\nCora De\u00dford, age 69, died at her\nhome near Grassy Creek last Thurs\nday and was laid to rest Saturday\nin the family cemetery.\nRevs. Lester Denney and Jeter\nBlevins conducted the service. The\npallbearers were Grover Shepard,\nI Wilburn Shepard, Jeter Pasley, O.\nand Wane Testerman, Webb Pasley,\nRondy Eller and Jewel Blevins.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe wish to thank our friends for\nthe kindness and sympathy shown\nduring the death and burial of O.\nD. Watts, which took place here last\nThursday.\nMR. and MRS. P. E. WATTS.\nTHE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\nHEADS INSURANCE CO.\nwWMwMBi\nMH\nJULIAN PRICE, who is president\nof the Jefferson Standard Life In\nsurance Company. Last year this\ncompany had one of its best years\nin history.\n\u201937 Record Year\nFor Insurance Co.\n1937 was the best year in the his\ntory of the Jefferson Standard Life\nInsurance Company, President Ju\nlian Price reported at the annual\nmetting of the stockholders held in\nGreensboro recently.\nAlthough there has been much\ntalk of a general business recession,\nthe Jefferson Standard enjoyed\n\u201csplendid gains along all lines dur\ning the past year\u201d, President Price\nstated in his annual report. Insur\nance in force wais increased by ap\nproximately $24,000,000, he said,\nand he remarked that this consti\nstuted the largest gain secured since\n1928. In each of the 26 states and\nin the District of Columbia and Pu\nerto Rico, the territory in which the\nCompany operates, there was a gain\nin insurance in force, it was shown.\nMr. Price reported that in 1937\nthe Company\u2019s sales of new life in\nsurance increased 7 per cent over\nthose of 1936, making the total\namount of new life insurance sold\nduring the year just closed $53,-\n600,000. Insurance in force now to\ntals $371,000,000, the largest amount\nin the history of the Company. Mor\ntality was extremely low just 53.6\nper cent of the expected, an im\nprovement of 6% by comparison\nwith the 1936 record, it was report\ned. The higher renewal record of\npolicies in force was mentioned as\nreflecting good general conditions\nin the territory occupied by the\nCompany.\nL. L. Scott 4s agent for Jefferson\nstandard\nWILEY EVERETTE BARE\nDIED FROM PNEUMONIA\nWiley Everette Bare, age 29, died\nwith pneumonia last week and was\nburied Thursday afternoon at the\nEbenezer Presbyterian church, of\nwhich he was a member. Funeral\nsarviices wore conducted by Rev.\nJ. W. Luke.\nMr. Bare had been suffering for\nsome time with heart trouble and\nwais unable to stand the strain of\npneumonia. He leaves his wife,\nand three children, Ruby, Joe and\nMarie. He is also survived by his\n\u201937 Farm Income\nJumps 13 Percent\nt\nBenefit Payments To Fanners\nTrippled 1936. Tobacco In\ncome Higher.\nNorth Carolina\u2019s principal farm\ncrops brought $196,578,000 in 1937,\nan increase of 13 per cent over 1936,\naccording to Julian Mann f extension\nstatistician at State College.\nThis increase of nearly $26,0d0,-\n000 was probably brought about by\nthe above-average prices received\nfor the bumper tobacco crop pro\nduced last year, Mann said.\nGovernment payments for parti\ncipation in the Agricultural Conser\nvation program jumped sharply in\n1937. In 1936 the payments amount\ned to $4,302,000, while last year\nfarmers received a total of $12,217,-\n000.\nReceipts from the sale of livestock\nproducts showed a slight decline in\n1937. In 1936 the figure was 2,-\n965,000; last year, it dropped off to\n$2,589,000.\nAdding livestock, crops, and gov\nernment payments together, the\n1937 total was $33,500,000 over that\nof the previous year.\nIn all major geographical divisions\nof the country, except the north\nwestern group, increases in farm\nincome were shown last year, Mann\npointed out.\nIn the South Atlantic division,\nSouth Carolina and Georgia were\nthe only states which slid back\nwards in 1937.\nThe favorable prices received for\ntobacco was perhaps the factor\nwhich kept North Carolina from\njoining these istates in a decreased\nincome, the statiscian declared.\nNext to Florida, this State has\nthe largest net increase in the\nsoutheastern division. Including\nFederal payments to farmers co\noperating in the conservation pro\ngram, North Carolina\u2019s increase was\n17 per cent.\nfather; Mr. and Mrs. D. C. Bare;\nthree brothers, Gilbert, Wayne and\nWalter and two sistens, Mrs. Rob\nert Woodie and Selma Bare.\n3 More Prizes Offered\nIn The Post\u2019s\nRecipe Contests\ns Kraft-Phenix Cheese Corp., Smithey\u2019s Dept. Store and Belk\u2019s\nI Dept. Store offer prizes for different Recipes, as shown below.\n\nEnter Contests Now!\nTHE POST IS OFFERING $16.00 in Cash AND THREE ONE\nYEAR SUBSCRIPTIONS IN TWO ASHE COUNTY RECIPE\nCONTESTS.\nCommunity Recipe\nContest Rules Os Contests:\nIst\n*l, These two contests will commence tomorrow, Fri-\n2nd. $3 Cash Feb, 11, and last for a limited time. (Closing\n3rd. $2 Cash date to be announced later.)\n2. All housewives and their daughters, ladies\u2019 com\n1* i -a tt munity clubs and organization are eligible to partici-\nJLllCllVlCtUal JtlOmC pate in these contests, but employees of The Post and\n-pw their immediate families are barred. Each organiza-\nJYIaKCrS Kccipc tion or individual is limited to three recipes.\n3 Recipes of all kinds, including meats, vegetables,\ncakes, pies, bpread, salads, etc., may be submitted and\nIst $3 Cash he given equal consideration by the judges. The\nj 1 ao r\u00ab u originality of recipes, however, is significant, as The\n3rd. SI.OO Cash county cooks prepare food. But recipes do not have to\nand three free sub- be orisinal They should be favorites\nscriptions. 4. Neatness, legibility, and accuracy of writing in\nE IKe rL nneo iTi-nfL PliAniv submitting each recipe are essential, but will be given\n5 Lbs. Cheese Krait-Fhemx only minor consideration. Only one recipe should be\nCheese Corp. For Best Recipe written on each sheet of paper and the Entries may be\non Dish Containing Cheese. sent to the Recipe Contest Editor, The Sky-\n12 Lb. Bag Queen of West g AU entered\nin the contests will become\nFlour\u2014Smithey\u2019s Store\u2014For the property of The Skyland Post and every effort will\nBest Bread, Cake or Pie Reci- be \u201cade to publish them as they are received.\npe\nF 6. At the close of the contest competent judges will\nPair Ladies\u2019 Hose Belk\u2019s be selected to determine the winners and their deci-\nDept. Store\u2014For Best Salad sions wUI be finaJ\nRecipe.\nENTER THE CONTEST NOW! ANYONE CAN WIN! HELP THE POST FIND OUT WHY\nASHE COUNTY FOOD AND ASHE COOKS ARE SO FAMOUS.\nSend Your Favorite Redoes To\nRecipe Contest Editor The Skyland Post\nAshe county cooks are famous for their cooking, and\nSmithey\u2019s is famous for its grocery values. We are offer-\ning a Recipe Prize and Many Bargains.\nHBOI\nCommet Uncoated Rice, lb. 8c\nPost Toasties Com Flakes, 8-oz. pkg 3 for 19c\nMarshmallows, 1 lb. package 15c\nPeanut Butter, 2 lb. jar. 25c\nPickford Salmon, No. 1 Tall Can 10c\nSalt, IV 2 lb. Box Table Salt 3 for 10c\n4 lb. Carton Lard 43\n8 lb. Carton Compound Lard 80c\nFranklin Granulated Sugar, 5 lb. bag 25c\nP G or OK Soap, large size 3 for 10c\nPure Arbuckle Coffee, 5 lb. pail 69c\nHeavy Fatback Meat, lb. 10c\nQueen of East Flour\n98 lb. bag $3.05\n48 lb. bag l\u00ab60\n24 lb. bag *BS\nSmithey\u2019s Store\nWEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\nTHURSDAY, FEBRUARY 24, 1938","height":"27444","width":"18774"}}
